4. Concurrent Rendering (React 18)
	â€¢	With Fiber + Scheduler, React can now do Concurrent Rendering:
	â€¢	Render phase is interruptible (can pause/resume/discard).
	â€¢	Commit phase is synchronous (always applies changes immediately).
	â€¢	Example: While rendering a huge list, if user types, React pauses rendering and updates input immediately.

ğŸ‘‰ Interview note: â€œConcurrent rendering doesnâ€™t make React faster, but makes apps feel faster by prioritizing urgent updates.â€

â¸»

5. Buffering
	â€¢	Buffering = holding back non-urgent updates until urgent ones finish.
	â€¢	APIs:
	â€¢	startTransition â†’ Mark some updates as low priority.
	â€¢	useDeferredValue â†’ Let React delay rendering derived values.
	â€¢	Example: Search box with 10,000 items
	â€¢	Typing (query) â†’ Urgent, updates immediately.
	â€¢	Filtering (results) â†’ Buffered until typing finishes.

ğŸ‘‰ Interview note: â€œBuffering keeps UI responsive by not blocking urgent updates with heavy tasks.â€

